ops.insert: This is a warmup tutorial for TunePad. By the end of this tutorial you'll be making your own music and writing your own code. In this tutorial, we're going to program a simple
from scratch. Variants of this beat pattern form the foundation for much of House, EDM, rock, and early hip-hop music.
TunePad is a tool for creating music using the

programming language. You don't need to be a musician or a programmer to get started. TunePad comes with ready-made samples and learning guides to help develop your new skills.
How TunePad Works
TunePad projects are made up of a collection

. Cells can be musical instruments like drums, bass, and keyboard, or they can be text cells like the one you're reading now. Text cells are a perfect place to jot down ideas or lyrics or links to videos and other media. Unlike other music creation software, all of the instruments in TunePad can be played using Python code.
This beat pattern is sometimes referred to as four-on-the-floor, meaning that we're going to pound out four solid
beats every measure. Take a look at the code in the drum track below and then press the
button to hear how it sounds.
In the code above, we used a TunePad statement called
. Every time we type a line of code with
, it adds a sound to our track. We're going to use this again in the next cell to add snare drum sounds on beats 2 and 4 (the upbeats). This time we're going to use another function called

to skip beats 1 and 3 (the downbeats).
Take a look at this cell and then try playing it while playing the kick drums at the same time.
In TunePad all of the cells synchronize together.
To give our beat a little more groove, we can add hi-hats in the spaces between the beats. Again, we use the
function to set up the timing between the beats. This time we're also going to tell
that we want to play shorter notes. We do this using the
parameter. Try playing all three cells together to get the full effect.

idata.author: Anonymous
idata.python:
rest(beats = 0.5) # rest for half of a beat

# play 2 hi-hat sounds for a fourth of a beat each
playNote(4, beats = 0.25) 
playNote(4, beats = 0.25)

rest(beats = 0.5)
playNote(4)
playNote(4)
playNote(4, beats = 0.5)

ops.insert: To wrap things up, let's add a simple bass line consisting of four notes.

idata.author: Anonymous
idata.python:
# simple bass line with a slide back to the root note
playNote(21, 4)
playNote(24, 4)
playNote(23, 4)
playNote(22, 3)
with bend(cents = [ 0, -100 ], beats=1):
    playNote(22, 1)
